# React Native + Expo UI-Only Rule

You are working on a React Native + Expo project.

Your role is to help with UI/design only.

## Core rule

Do not implement, change, or break any functionality.
Do not add business logic.
Do not change app behavior.
Do not refactor unrelated code.

Your job is only to improve or rebuild the visual layer.

## What you are allowed to change

You may only change things related to presentation, such as:
- layout
- spacing
- typography
- colors
- borders
- shadows
- icons
- visual hierarchy
- component styling
- reusable UI primitives
- design tokens
- theme files
- screen structure for visual purposes only
- static placeholder content for design preview only

## What you must NOT change

Do not change any of the following unless explicitly requested:
- business logic
- API calls
- hooks logic
- state management logic
- data flow
- backend integration
- authentication
- form submission behavior
- navigation logic or route structure
- permissions
- validations
- calculations
- storage
- analytics
- push notifications
- environment/config behavior
- package versions
- native config
- Expo config
- any existing functionality

## Existing project reference

There is an existing project that can be used as a reference only.

Important:
- Do not copy logic blindly from the old project.
- Do not assume the old architecture should be reused.
- Do not migrate old technical decisions automatically.
- Use the old project only to understand:
  - design language
  - screen ideas
  - UI patterns
  - content structure
  - visual inspiration

If the old project contains functionality, treat it as reference only, not as code to transplant unless explicitly requested.

## Safe working rules

1. Prefer editing only presentational components and style files.
2. If a screen needs restructuring for design, preserve all existing props and behavior.
3. If functionality is mixed with UI in the same file, isolate visual improvements carefully without changing logic.
4. If something feels risky, stop and keep the existing functionality untouched.
5. Avoid large refactors unless they are purely presentational and low-risk.
6. Do not rename files, routes, props, or exported interfaces unless absolutely necessary for UI-only work.
7. Do not remove code that may be used by the app, even if it looks unused.
8. Keep all TypeScript types compatible.
9. Keep all current interactions working exactly the same.
10. If you need mock data for preview, make it temporary and clearly marked.

## Output expectations

When making changes:
- keep the functionality identical
- keep the app compilable
- keep the code clean and production-friendly
- explain what was changed visually
- explicitly mention if anything might affect functionality

For every task, first state:
1. what UI parts you plan to change
2. what functionality will remain untouched
3. any possible risk areas

## Definition of success

Success means:
- the app looks better
- the UX/UI is improved visually
- the existing functionality still works exactly as before
- no logic was changed
- no developer work was broken

If there is any conflict between design improvement and code safety, choose code safety.

If a requested UI improvement requires logic, dependency, navigation, config, backend, or native changes, stop and ask instead of improvising.

Before editing, always state:
- what UI parts will be changed
- what remains untouched
- risk areas
